item.title: Félix Sanz Roldán
item.description: Félix Sanz Roldán (born 20 January 1945) is a retired Spanish Army general and intelligence officer who served as Director of the National Intelligence Centre (CNI) from July 2009 to July 2019.[1] He served as Chief of the Defence Staff (JEMAD) of the Spanish Armed Forces during the first government of prime minister José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero (2004–2008).[2]

item.title: 2010 Wigan Metropolitan Borough Council election
item.description: Elections to Wigan Council were held on 6 May 2010. One-third of the council was up for election.[1][2][3]

item.title: HAT-P-65
item.description: HAT-P-65 is a faint star located in the equatorial constellation Equuleus. With an apparent magnitude of 13.16, it requires a telescope to be seen. The star is located 2,460 light-years (750 pc) away from Earth,[2] but is drifting close with a radial velocity of -48 km/s.

item.title: Portland Breakwater Light
item.description: The Portland Breakwater Light (also called Bug Light) is a small lighthouse in South Portland, Maine, United States.[2][3]

item.title: The Inhabitant of the Lake and Less Welcome Tenants
item.description: The Inhabitant of the Lake and Less Welcome Tenants is a collection of fantasy and horror short stories by British author J. Ramsey Campbell, who dropped the initial from his name in subsequent publications. Initially announced under the title The Box in the Priory [1] it was released in 1964 by Arkham House in an edition of 2,009 copies and was the author's first book. The stories are part of the Cthulhu Mythos. Campbell had originally written his introduction to be included in the book The Dark Brotherhood and Other Pieces under the title "Cthulhu in Britain". However, Arkham's editor, August Derleth, decided to use it here (retitled "A Word from the Author").
